\begin_layout Standard
Conside the following probability distribution of ratings, written in matrix
 form for convenience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0.216 & 0.016 & 0.048\\
0.024 & 0.224 & 0.072\\
0.040 & 0.040 & 0.320
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

The marginal distributions are 
\begin_inset Formula $g=[0.2,0.3,0.5]$
\end_inset

 for rater 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h=[0.2,0.2,0.6]$
\end_inset

 for rater 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=gh^{T}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0.04 & 0.04 & 0.12\\
0.06 & 0.06 & 0.18\\
0.10 & 0.18 & 0.30
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

the value of Cohen's kappa equals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa=\frac{\tr F-\tr G}{1-\tr G}=0.6.
\]

\end_inset

Consider the following convex decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\lambda H^{\lambda}+(1-\lambda)G,\quad\lambda\in(0,1).\label{eq:decomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Putting 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\kappa=0.6,$
\end_inset

 we find that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-\kappa)G=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
0.016 & 0.016 & 0.048\\
0.024 & 0.024 & 0.072\\
0.040 & 0.040 & 0.120
\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset

hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\kappa\frac{1}{3}I+(1-\kappa)G,\quad(H^{\kappa}=\frac{1}{3}I).
\]

\end_inset

We make the following observations: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The smallest possible value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a probability distribution is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 For if it is any smaller, the off-diagonal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda)G$
\end_inset

 will dominate the off-diagonal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, implying that 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 won't be a probability distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\kappa}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal, hence its probability of agreement 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr H^{\kappa}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From these observations we believe the following makes a reasonable agreement
 coefficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:agreement definition"

\end_inset

The agreement of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{(F,G)}=\lambda_{\min}\tr H^{\lambda_{\min}},\label{eq:kappa_(F,G)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\max}$
\end_inset

 is the maximal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda H^{\lambda}+(1-\lambda)G$
\end_inset

 is a probability distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, we have that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{\lambda}=\frac{F-(1-\lambda)G}{\lambda}.
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\min}=1-\min_{G_{ij}\neq0}\left(\frac{F_{ij}}{G_{ij}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

so we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,G)}$
\end_inset

 as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{(F,G)}=\tr(F)-\min_{G_{ij}\neq0}\left(\frac{F_{ij}}{G_{ij}}\right)\tr(G).\label{eq:kappa_(F,G) reformulation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For the example above 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr(F)=0.76$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr G=0.4$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{G_{ij}\neq0}(F_{ij}/G_{ij})=0.4$
\end_inset

, hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{(F,G)}=0.76-0.4^{2}=0.60.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must make clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,G)}$
\end_inset

 is not a generalization of Cohen's kappa.
 To see why, consider a matrix that cannot be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda D+(1-\lambda)gh^{T}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is diagonal and 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h$
\end_inset

 are the marginal probabilities.
 Most matrices are on this form.
 For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\frac{1}{18^{2}}\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
36 & 18 & 36\\
18 & 54 & 54\\
54 & 18 & 36
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Calculations show that Cohen's kappa equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\approx0.088$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=\frac{1}{18}[6,5,7]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\frac{1}{18}[5,7,6]$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=gh^{T}=\frac{1}{18^{2}}\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
30 & 25 & 35\\
42 & 35 & 49\\
36 & 30 & 42
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

There is no parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 where the off-diagonal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda)G$
\end_inset

 equals the off-diagonal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda_{\max}}$
\end_inset

isn't diagonal; hence its percent agreement is different from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 We can calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\max}=1-18/42\approx0.43$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr H^{\lambda_{\max}}\approx0.43$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,G)}=0.247$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda_{\max}}$
\end_inset

 is far from diagonal, being
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{\lambda_{\max}}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\\
\\
\\
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:agreement definition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 defines the agreement for any pair 
\begin_inset Formula $F,G$
\end_inset

, but the most important cases occur when 
\begin_inset Formula $G=gh^{T}$
\end_inset

 for two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a rank 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 Provided the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda_{\max}}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal, it is straight-forward to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,G)}$
\end_inset

 equals Fleiss' kappa when 
\begin_inset Formula $G=ff^{T}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\frac{1}{2}(g+h)$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h$
\end_inset

 are the marginals of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,C^{-2}I)}$
\end_inset

 equals the Brennan–Prediger coefficient too.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This naturally leads us to consider decompositions of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\lambda D+(1-\lambda)gh^{T},\quad D\text{ is diagonal}.
\]

\end_inset

One can show that this decomposition, if it exists, is unique provided 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 isn't already diagonal.
 Call distributions of this form 
\begin_inset Formula $gh^{T}$
\end_inset

-decomposable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are endless arguments in the agreement literature about which agreement
 coefficient to prefer.
 Should you use Cohen's kappa, Fleiss' kappa, or perhaps the Brennan–Prediger
 coefficient? In our context these questions are about choosing the form
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h$
\end_inset

.
 We propose to do the following, on the population level:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $gh^{T}$
\end_inset

-decomposable.
 Since the decomposition is unique, report the agreement of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $gh^{T}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,gh^{T})}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is not decomposable.
 Find the diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, probability vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 that minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $||F-(\lambda D+(1-\lambda)gh^{T}||$
\end_inset

 subject to the constrant that 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{T}D1=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then report 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\tr D$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
