\begin_layout Standard
We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $G=gh^{T}$
\end_inset

 for two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{T}g=1^{T}h=1$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are probability distributions over the categories 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,2,\ldots,C\}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\lambda H^{\lambda}+(1-\lambda)G,\quad\lambda\in[0,1].
\]

\end_inset

A decomposition is admissible if 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a non-negative matrix.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}=F$
\end_inset

, every 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has an admissible decomposition.
 A non-trivial admissible decomposition occurs when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<1$
\end_inset

.
 There is a non-trivial admissible decomposition iff the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is contained in the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, we can define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{\lambda}=\frac{F-(1-\lambda)G}{\lambda}.
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\min}=\min_{G_{ij}\neq0}\left(\frac{F_{ij}}{G_{ij}}\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{(F,G)}=\tr(F)-\min_{G_{ij}\neq0}\left(\frac{F_{ij}}{G_{ij}}\right)\tr(G)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=gh^{T}$
\end_inset

 be a rank 1 matrix with only positive elements summing to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

-agreement of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{G}=\lambda_{\min}\tr H^{\lambda_{\min}}=\tr(F)-(1-\lambda_{\min})\tr(G),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\min}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is non-negative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's easy to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{\min}=1-\min(F_{ij}/G_{ij}),\label{eq:lambda_min}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where elements with 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 are ignored.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda_{\min}}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\min}=\tr(F)-(1-\lambda_{\min})\tr(G),$
\end_inset

which implies that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{G}=\lambda_{\min}=\frac{\tr(F)-\tr(G)}{1-\tr(G)}.
\]

\end_inset

Since the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, we see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\lambda_{\min}=\kappa_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 won't be diagonal in general.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr H^{\lambda}<0$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\min}>\frac{\tr(F)-\tr(G)}{1-\tr(G)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xc=a-(1-x)b
\]

\end_inset

implies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\min}=\frac{\tr(F)-\tr(G)}{\tr H^{\lambda_{\min}}-\tr G}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tr(H^{\lambda})=\frac{\tr(F)-(1-\lambda)\tr(G)}{\lambda}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{G}=\tr(F)-(\min(F_{ij}/G_{ij}))\tr(G)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the distribution matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
118 & 5\\
2 & 0
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{22}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,G)}=\tr F=0.944$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $G=gh^{T}$
\end_inset

 except 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{(F,G)}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let's try to understand why this happens.
 There are two plausible ways that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 could be generated.
 In the first model, the raters place every item into the first category
 on autopilot except in very special circumstances, where they have think.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A new kind of agreement measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a provided distribution.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, define 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=\lambda H^{\lambda}+(1-\lambda)G.
\]

\end_inset

Hypothesis: 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{G}=\lambda_{\min}p_{A}(H^{\lambda_{\max}})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is chosen so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H^{\lambda}=\frac{F-(1-\lambda)G}{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

 is a probability distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The percent agreement of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p_{A}(F)-(1-\lambda)p_{A}(G)}{\lambda}
\]

\end_inset

Which equal chance agreement iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\frac{p_{A}(F)-p_{A}(G)}{1-p_{A}(G)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof: For 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 to be a distribution we only require every element 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{ij}^{\lambda}\geq0$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $F-(1-\lambda)G$
\end_inset

 is a non-negative matrix.
 (That the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 sums to 1 happens automatically.) This is possible if and only 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda)G_{ij}\leq F_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

.
 and the minimal 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\min}=1-\min(f_{ij}/g_{ij})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence a natural measure of disagreement is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{\min}p_{A}(H^{\lambda_{\min}})=p_{A}(F)-(1-\lambda_{\min})p_{A}(G).
\]

\end_inset

Now consider the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\lambda_{\min}}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal.
 In other words there is perfect agreement between the raters.
 In this case,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{A}(H^{\lambda_{\min}})=1.
\]

\end_inset

Hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lambda_{\min} & = & p_{A}(F)-(1-\lambda_{\min})p_{A}(G),\\
 & = & \frac{p_{A}(F)-p_{A}(G)}{1-p_{A}(G)}.\\
 & = & \frac{\tr(F)-\tr(G)}{1-\tr(G)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Finding the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following question: For what 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

s is it the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $F-(1-\lambda)G$
\end_inset

 is diagonal for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

? We need the off-diagonal elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda)G$
\end_inset

 to be equal to the off-diagonal.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1-\lambda)(G-\diag(G))=F-\diag(F).
\]

\end_inset

Which implies that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F-(1-\lambda)(G-\diag G)=\diag(F).
\]

\end_inset

This is possible for infinitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, but let's restrict ourselves to the case to the rank 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 case, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $G=gh^{T}$
\end_inset

 for two non-negative vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{T}g=1^{T}h=1$
\end_inset

.
 It's not, in general, possible to approximate the off-diagonal elements
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with a rank 1 matrix.
 If it is possible to do this, then the solution is unique since the diagonal
 elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=(1-\lambda)gh^{T}+D,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{T}D1=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{T}F1=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{T}gh^{T}1=1$
\end_inset

, it follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tr G=D.
\]

\end_inset

